723752f-a.title: Manhattan: Varick Street - Dominick Street
723752f-a.text:
117 and 125-135 Varick Street (Vhe American News Building), west
side, at Dominick Street. Nos. 123 and 119-121, at and adjoining
the S.W. corner, have been demolished. The American News Building.
on the west side from Dominick to Spring Streets, was built about 1923.
February 12, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.

719328f-a.title: Manhattan: Dominick Street - Varick Street
719328f-a.text:
DDominick Street, south side, from Varick Street to Sixth Avenue,
showing the old frame house No. 14 and the Dominick Street side
of Public School No. 38, at and adjoining what is now the west
side of Sixth Avenue but used to be Clark Street. There used to
be three more old houses in the block,Nos. 16-20 Dominick Street,
adjoining the corner of Varick Street; they were taken down not
long after 1922.
1932.
J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.
Negative No. 581.

719327f-b.title: Manhattan: Dominick Street - Varick Street
719327f-b.text:
(1)
Dominick Street, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of Varick
Street, showing the dormitory and gymnasium of Varick House.
February 28, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, from a different angle. Also shown is Varick Street,
east side, north from and including Dominick to Spring Streets.
Included is a rear view of the Spring Street Presbyterian Church
located on Spring Street at the S.E. corner of Varick Street.
July 27, 1935.
P. L. Sperr.

723754f-a.title: Manhattan: Varick Street - Dominick Street
723754f-a.text:
Varick Street, south from Dominick Street. In the background,
on the east side of the street, may be seen the spire of St. John's
Chapel. This picture was taken before the widening of Varick Street
(at the expense of the east side) in 1914-15.
About 1912.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

723755f-a.title: Manhattan: Varick Street - Dominick Street
723755f-a.text:
127-29 Varick Street, adjoining and north of the N. W.
corner of Dominick Street, showing two frame 2 1-2 story
residences. The buildings at the left and right margins
are also of frame construction; that at the left (corner
structure) having a brick shell. Note the alley that
separates No's. 129 and 131.
About 1900
J. J. Corell, photo
P. L. Sperr Collection
